   Assertions - Method 1: Immediate vs Concurrent

  ### 1. Immediate Assertions

  • What it is: A basic security guard that only checks the rules at the exact millisecond the code is executed. It works exactly like a
  normal  if  statement.
  • Why it is used: To do a quick, simple check on combinatorial logic or simple values.
  • The Limitation: It has no concept of time! If you ask an Immediate Assertion, "Did the request signal go high 3 clock cycles ago?" it
  will fail because it cannot look into the past or the future.
  • Syntax:
   assert (condition) pass_message else fail_message;

  ### 2. Concurrent Assertions (The Real Power of SVA)

  • What it is: An advanced security guard that understands time. It runs continuously in the background in parallel with your other code,
  constantly watching the clock.
  • Why it is used: Almost everything in hardware design involves time! (e.g., "If I send a read request, the data MUST arrive exactly 2
  clock cycles later."). Only a Concurrent Assertion can test this.
  • How it is built: It uses a 3-step building block:
      1. Sequence: Define the timing relationship (e.g., Signal A, then wait 2 clocks for Signal B).
      2. Property: Put the sequence inside a property and tie it to a  clock  so it knows how fast to count.
      3. Assert: Turn the property on.


  ### 1. What is  immediate_guard: ?

  It is not a variable! It is just a Label (a name).
  In SystemVerilog, you are allowed to give a name to your assertion by putting a name and a colon ( : ) in front of it.

  •  my_cool_name: assert(A == 1);
  • Why do we do this? If you have 100 assertions and one of them fails, the simulator error log will say "Assertion my_cool_name failed!" If
  you don't use labels, the simulator will just say "Assertion #87 failed" and you won't know which one it is!

  ### 2. How can you write  else  without an  if ?

  This is a very special rule for Assertions!
  In normal coding, you are right:  else  must always follow an  if .
  But the  assert  keyword is special. It acts exactly like an  if  statement built into one word.
  You literally read it in English like this: "Assert that this is true, Else print an error!"
