   Method 1: Immediate vs Concurrent Assertions

  ## PART A: Immediate Assertions

  • What is it?
      • Simple: It is a basic check that happens instantly at one exact moment in time.
      • Proper Definition: An immediate assertion is a test of an expression performed when the statement is executed in the procedural code.
      If it evaluates to false, the assertion fails.
  • Why is it used? We use it to do quick, simple math checks or check simple combinatorial logic where we don't care about the clock.
  • How is it used? You must put it inside a procedural block (like an  always  block or  initial  block).
  • Syntax:
    // [label:] assert (condition) [pass_statement] else [fail_statement];

    always @(posedge clk) begin
      my_label: assert (A == B) $display("Pass!"); else $error("Fail!");
    end


  ## PART B: Concurrent Assertions

  • What is it?
      • Simple: It is an advanced check that watches your signals continuously over time. It always needs a clock!
      • Proper Definition: A concurrent assertion checks the sequence of events spread over multiple clock cycles. It executes in parallel
      with other blocks and is evaluated only at clock ticks.
  • Why is it used? Hardware takes time! If a signal must stay high for 5 clock cycles, an Immediate assertion cannot check that. Only a
  Concurrent assertion can measure time.
  • How is it used? You build a  property  to hold the timing rule and the clock. Then, you use  assert property  outside of your always
  blocks to turn it on.
  • Syntax:
    // 1. Create the rulebook (property)
    property my_rule;
      @(posedge clk) // Define the clock
      (A == B);      // Define the rule
    endproperty

    // 2. Turn it on
    // [label:] assert property (property_name) [pass] else [fail];

    my_guard: assert property (my_rule) $display("Pass!"); else $error("Fail!");


  Assertions - Method 2: Sequences and Timing Delays ( ## )

  In Method 1, we only checked if a rule was true at one specific moment in time (like  A == B ). But in real hardware design, things don't
  happen instantly. We need to measure time!

  ### 1. What is a Sequence and a Timing Delay?

  • Simple Explanation: A sequence is a timeline of events. Instead of just checking one variable, it checks a chain of events that happen
  one after another. To measure the time between these events, we use the Timing Delay Operator ( ## ).
  • Proper Definition: An SVA Sequence is a building block that expands Boolean expressions over more than one clock cycle. The  ##  operator
  specifies a delay of n clock cycles between expressions.

  ### 2. Why do we use it?

  Hardware has strict timing rules. For example, if a CPU sends a  read_request  to memory, the memory might take exactly 3 clock cycles to
  reply with  data_ready .
  If  data_ready  arrives in 2 clock cycles, the CPU might crash! If it arrives in 4 clock cycles, it is too slow!
  We use Sequences and Timing Delays to prove that the hardware waited the exact correct amount of time.

  ### 3. How do we use it? (The Syntax)

  The syntax uses the  ##  symbol, which simply means "Wait this many clock cycles."

  •  ##1  means "wait 1 clock cycle" (check on the next clock edge).
  •  ##5  means "wait 5 clock cycles".

  Syntax structure:

    // 1. Create a sequence timeline
    sequence my_timeline;

      // Read this as: "A must be 1, then WAIT 3 clock cycles, then B must be 1"
      A ##3 B;

    endsequence

    // 2. Put the sequence inside a property with a clock
    property my_timing_rule;
      @(posedge clk) my_timeline;
    endproperty

### 2. "Why use  $time  in the display?"

   $time  is just a built-in SystemVerilog stopwatch. It tells you the exact time in the simulation.
  If you don't use  $time , the log just says: "ERROR: Timing rule broken!"
  If you use  $time , the log says: "ERROR: Timing rule broken at 45ns!"
  This makes it 100x easier for you to open the waveform and look exactly at 45ns to see what went wrong.

  ### 3. "Why do we need a  sequence  block? Isn't  property  enough?"

  You are 100% correct! You do not need a separate  sequence  block. You can write the timeline directly inside the property like this:

    property my_timing_rule;
      @(posedge clk) (req == 1) ##2 (ack == 1);
    endproperty

  So why do engineers use  sequence ? Because it acts like a reusable function. If you have a very complex timeline, you can put it inside a
  sequence  block once, and then reuse it inside 10 different properties without typing it all over again. A "timeline of events" just means
  "A happens, then wait a bit, then B happens".

  ### 4. "What did you mean by the HUGE PROBLEM?"

  Let's go back to the restaurant.
  Imagine the restaurant manager comes up to your table every 5 seconds and yells at you: "Why didn't you get your pizza yet?!"
  You would reply: "Because I haven't ordered yet (Req is 0)!!"

  The assertion is exactly like that annoying manager. Because the assertion runs on every single clock tick, it does this:

  • Clock 1: Is Req 1? No! -> FAIL ERROR!
  • Clock 2: Is Req 1? No! -> FAIL ERROR!
  • Clock 3: You finally make a Request (Req is 1). Wait 2 clocks. Ack is 1. -> PASS!

  We don't want the assertion yelling at us when we haven't even made a request! We want to tell the assertion: "Do not start checking UNLESS
  (IF) Req is 1."

  This is why we desperately need the next topic: Implication Operators (If-Then statements).

