   Assertions - Method 3: Implication Operators ( |->  and  |=> )

  ### 1. What is an Implication Operator?

  • Simple Explanation: It is an If-Then statement built specifically for assertions.
  • Proper Definition: An implication operator tells the assertion to only evaluate the right-hand side (Consequent) IF the left-hand side
  (Antecedent) is true. If the left-hand side is false, the assertion simply ignores it and does not throw an error.

  ### 2. Why do we use it?

  To solve the exact bug you just found! Without it, an assertion will desperately try to test your rule on every single clock tick. If you
  use an Implication Operator, it tells the assertion: "Go to sleep. Only wake up and check the rule IF the request goes high."

  ### 3. How do we use it? (The Syntax)

  There are two types of implication operators. This is a guaranteed interview question, so memorize the difference!

  A) Overlapped Implication ( |-> )

  • Rule: If the left side is true, check the right side on the SAME clock cycle.
  • Syntax:  (A == 1) |-> (B == 1);  (If A is 1 right now, B must also be 1 right now).

  B) Non-Overlapped Implication ( |=> )

  • Rule: If the left side is true, check the right side on the NEXT clock cycle.
  • Syntax:  (A == 1) |=> (B == 1);  (If A is 1 right now, B must be 1 on the next clock tick).

  Here is the strict rule: You are NOT ALLOWED to put the  |->  symbol inside a  sequence  block!

  If you try to write this code:

    sequence req_ack_seq;
      (req == 1) |-> ##2 (ack == 1); // SYNTAX ERROR!!
    endsequence

  The simulator will throw a strict Syntax Error and crash!

  Why?

  • A  sequence  is only allowed to hold time delays ( ## ).
  • The  |->  symbol is an "If-Then" condition. In SystemVerilog, "If-Then" conditions are only allowed inside a  property .
  Assertions - Method 4: Repetition Operators

   Assertions - Method 4: Repetition Operators

  ### 1. What is a Repetition Operator?

  • Simple Explanation: It is a shortcut. Instead of writing  A ##1 A ##1 A  to check if  A  stays high for 3 clock cycles, you can just
  write  A[*3] .
  • Proper Definition: A repetition operator is used to specify that a signal or a sequence will match repeatedly for a specified number of
  clock cycles.
  • Why is it used? To make complex timing checks much easier to read and write.

  ### 2. The Two Types You Must Know (Syntax & How they are used)

  A) Consecutive Repetition ( [*n] )

  • The Rule: The signal must be true for  n  clock cycles in a row. There cannot be any gaps!
  • Syntax:  A[*3]
  • Example: If A is  1, 1, 1 , it passes. If A is  1, 0, 1, 1 , it fails because there was a  0  interrupting it!

  B) Go-To Repetition ( [->n] )

  • The Rule: The signal must be true for  n  clock cycles, but gaps are allowed. It does not have to be in a row!
  • Syntax:  A[->3]
  • Example: If A is  1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 1 , it passes! The assertion just waits patiently until it counts three  1 s.
  ──────



  Assertions - Method 5:  disable iff

  ### 1. What is it?

  • Simple Explanation: It is a "Kill Switch" for your assertion. If the kill switch is pulled, the assertion immediately turns off, stops
  checking, and ignores all errors.
  • Proper Definition: The  disable iff  (if and only if) clause allows an evaluation of a concurrent assertion to be preempted (killed) if a
  specified condition becomes true.

  ### 2. Why do we use it?

  For System Resets!
  Imagine you have an assertion running that says: "If Request is 1, Acknowledge must be 1 in 2 clock cycles."
  Suddenly, someone presses the physical  RESET  button on your chip. All signals are forced to  0 .
  Because Acknowledge was forced to  0 , your assertion will scream FAIL!
  But it's not a bug! The chip was just resetting! We use  disable iff (reset)  to tell the assertion: "Go to sleep and ignore all rules
  while the chip is resetting."

  ### 3. How do we use it? (Syntax)

  You put it directly inside the property, before the rule starts.
   disable iff (condition) rule;



 ──────
   Assertions - Method 6: Formal Arguments

  ### 1. What is it?

  • Simple Explanation: It allows you to pass variables into a  sequence  or  property , exactly the same way you pass variables into a
  function  or a  task !
  • Proper Definition: Formal arguments allow you to create parameterized sequences and properties. Instead of hard-coding specific signal
  names, you use generic placeholders, and pass the actual signals in when you call the property.

  ### 2. Why do we use it? (The Reusability Secret)

  Imagine you are designing a massive CPU. It has 3 different memory banks, which means it has 3 sets of Request/Acknowledge signals:

  1.  req_A  and  ack_A
  2.  req_B  and  ack_B
  3.  req_C  and  ack_C

  Without formal arguments, you would have to type out three completely separate sequences and properties, wasting time and making your code
  bloated!
  With formal arguments, you write ONE generic sequence, and you just pass the different signals into it like a function.

  ### 3. How do we use it? (The Syntax)

  You add parentheses  ()  after the sequence or property name, and define the generic argument names inside them.

    // 'req_sig' and 'ack_sig' are just generic placeholders!
    sequence generic_seq (req_sig, ack_sig);
      (req_sig == 1) |-> ##2 (ack_sig == 1);
    endsequence
    ──────



  Assertions - Method 7: Variable Delays

  ### 1. What is it?

  • Simple Explanation: Instead of hard-coding a strict number like  ##2  (always wait 2 clocks), you use a variable like  ##my_delay  so the
  delay can change while the simulation is running!
  • Proper Definition: It is the ability to use a variable or formal argument inside the timing delay operator ( ## ) to create dynamic,
  flexible timing checks.

  ### 2. Why do we use it?

  Not all hardware has a fixed timing rule!
  Imagine a Memory Chip that has two modes:

  1. Fast Mode: It replies in 2 clock cycles.
  2. Slow Mode: It replies in 5 clock cycles.

  If we hardcode  ##2 , the assertion will falsely crash when the memory is in Slow Mode.
  Instead, we pass a variable  delay_time  into the assertion. If the memory is in Fast Mode, we set  delay_time = 2 . If it is in Slow Mode,
  we set  delay_time = 5 . One assertion handles both modes perfectly!

  ### 3. How do we use it? (The Syntax)

  We combine it with Formal Arguments (Method 6) to pass the delay number into the property!

    // We create a formal argument 'delay_val'
    property dynamic_timing (req, ack, delay_val);
      @(posedge clk)

      // We put the variable directly after the ## symbol!
      (req == 1) |-> ##delay_val (ack == 1);

    endproperty



 ### Answering your 4 Questions:

  1. "Why the  1  in first?"
  In SystemVerilog, you cannot just do math in an assertion. You must check a condition first.  1  is just the boolean value for TRUE. By
  writing  (1, count = count - 1) , we are saying: "Condition is True, so do the math!" It is just a dummy placeholder.
  2. "What does  [*1:$]  represent?"
  This is the engine! It means "Repeat the previous step from 1 to Infinity ( $ ) times, advancing one clock tick every time." This is what
  forces the math to be slow! It can only subtract once per clock cycle.
  3. "What is  first_match ?"
  It is the Emergency Brake. Because  [*1:$]  says "Repeat to Infinity", the simulator would keep subtracting forever and crash.  first_match
  tells the simulator: "The exact millisecond the condition is met, smash the brakes, stop the loop, and move on!"
  ──────
  ### Timeline 1: How Delay = 2 actually takes 2 clock cycles

  Let's pretend we are the simulator. We pass in  memory_delay = 2 .

  • Clock 0 (The Start):  req = 1 . We copy the delay into the bucket:  count = 2 .
  • Clock 1: The  [*1:$]  loop runs for the first time.
      • We subtract 1.  count  is now  1 .
      • Is  count <= 0 ? No! (1 is not 0).
      • Result: We must wait for the next clock.
  • Clock 2: The  [*1:$]  loop runs for the second time.
      • We subtract 1.  count  is now  0 .
      • Is  count <= 0 ? YES! (0 is 0).
      • Result: The  first_match  keyword smashes the emergency brakes! The loop stops. We immediately check if  ack == 1 .
  • Conclusion: It took exactly 2 clock cycles for the math to reach 0!
  ──────
  ### Timeline 2: How Delay = 5 takes 5 clock cycles

  Now we pass in  memory_delay = 5 .

  • Clock 0 (The Start):  req = 1 . We copy the delay into the bucket:  count = 5 .
  • Clock 1: We subtract 1.  count  = 4. (Not zero, keep waiting).
  • Clock 2: We subtract 1.  count  = 3. (Not zero, keep waiting).
  • Clock 3: We subtract 1.  count  = 2. (Not zero, keep waiting).
  • Clock 4: We subtract 1.  count  = 1. (Not zero, keep waiting).
  • Clock 5: We subtract 1.  count  = 0. YES!  first_match  stops the loop. We check  ack == 1 .
  • Conclusion: Because we started with a bigger number, the simulator was forced to wait for 5 clock ticks before the math reached 0!

  This is how the subtraction dynamically creates the delay! The bigger the number you pour into the bucket, the more clock cycles the
  simulator is forced to wait before it reaches zero!


