  ### Missed Topic 2: Multiple sequences

  In your previous code, you wrote the sequence on the left side, and the property on the right side. But the textbook allows you to define
  two separate sequences and chain them together inside the property!

  • What is it? Combining two different sequences using the implication operator ( |-> ).
  • Why use it? It makes your code much cleaner if you have very long rules.

  Syntax:

    // Sequence A (The Trigger)
    sequence seqA;
      (req && enable); // (This is our logical expression from Topic 1!)
    endsequence

    // Sequence B (The Check)
    sequence seqB;
      ##5 (ack == 1);
    endsequence

    // We chain them together here!
    property multiple_seq_prop;
      @(posedge clk)
      seqA |-> seqB; // "If Sequence A is true |-> check Sequence B"
    endproperty

  Inch-by-Inch Explanation:

  1. The assertion waits for the clock edge.
  2. It checks  seqA . (Are  req  and  enable  BOTH high right now?)
  3. If yes, the  |->  triggers!
  4. It moves to  seqB , waits exactly 5 clock cycles, and checks if  ack  is 1.



