  ### Missed Topic 4: Non-consecutive Repetition ( [=n] )

  To understand this, we must quickly look at the three brothers of Repetition:

  1. The Strict Brother ( [*3]  Consecutive):  b  MUST be high for 3 clocks perfectly in a row. No gaps allowed!
  2. The Middle Brother ( [->3]  Go-To):  b  must be high 3 times (gaps allowed). BUT, the exact moment the 3rd  b  arrives, you must
  immediately jump to the next rule!
  3. The Chill Brother ( [=3]  Non-consecutive):  b  must be high 3 times (gaps allowed). AND, after the 3rd  b  arrives, you can just wait
  around and relax until the next rule happens!

  ### The Difference between  [->3]  and  [=3]

  Let's look at a rule where  c  must happen after 3  b s:

  Rule 1: Go-To ( [->3] )

    property goto_prop;
      @(posedge clk) (a == 1) |-> b[->3] ##1 c;
    endproperty

  • The Timeline:  b  happens once. We wait.  b  happens twice. We wait.  b  happens a third time!
  • The Check: Because we used  [->3] , the simulator demands that  c  is high on the very next clock cycle ( ##1 ). If  c  waits 5 clocks to
  arrive, the assertion FAILS!

  Rule 2: Non-consecutive ( [=3] )

    property noncon_prop;
      @(posedge clk) (a == 1) |-> b[=3] ##1 c;
    endproperty

  • The Timeline:  b  happens once. We wait.  b  happens twice. We wait.  b  happens a third time!
  • The Check: Because we used  [=3] , the simulator says: "We found our 3 b's! I don't care when  c  happens.  c  can happen on the next
  clock, or  c  can wait 20 clocks to arrive!"
  • As long as  c  eventually arrives (and no more  b s happen in between), the assertion PASSES!

  ### Summary:

  • Use  [->3]  if the next event must happen immediately after the 3rd match.
  • Use  [=3]  if the next event can happen anytime after the 3rd match.



  #### 1.  $rose(signal)

  • What it does: It checks if the signal just transitioned from  0  to  1 .
  • The Rule: It returns TRUE only if the signal was  0  on the previous clock cycle, and is  1  on the current clock cycle.
  • Example:

    property p_rose;
      @(posedge clk) $rose(req);
    endproperty

  (If  req  was 1 on the last clock, and is still 1 on this clock,  $rose  is FALSE because it didn't just "rise" right now!)

  #### 2.  $fell(signal)

  • What it does: It checks if the signal just transitioned from  1  to  0  (falling edge).
  • The Rule: It returns TRUE only if the signal was  1  on the previous clock cycle, and is  0  on the current clock cycle.
  • Example:

    property p_fell;
      // If req goes high, ack MUST fall to 0!
      @(posedge clk) (req == 1) |-> $fell(ack);
    endproperty

  #### 3.  $stable(signal)

  • What it does: It checks if the signal stayed the exact same!
  • The Rule: It returns TRUE only if the signal has the exact same value ( 0  or  1 ) as it did on the previous clock cycle. No transitions
  allowed!
  • Example:

    property p_stable;
      // If enable is 0, the data signal is NOT allowed to change!
      @(posedge clk) (enable == 0) |-> $stable(data);
    endproperty

  This is heavily used in memory designs to make sure data isn't accidentally overwritten when the chip is turned off!



 ### Family 2: Time Travel ( $past )

  Normally, assertions are always looking into the future (using  ##2 ). But what if you want to look into the past?

  #### 4.  $past(signal, number_of_clocks)

  • What it does: It provides the exact value that a signal had a specific number of clock cycles ago.
  • Syntax:

    property p_past;
      // "If Ack is 1 right now, then 2 clocks ago, Req MUST have been 1!"
      @(posedge clk) (ack == 1) |-> ($past(req, 2) == 1);
    endproperty

  ### Why is this useful?

  It is just a different way of writing rules!
  Instead of standing at the  req  signal and looking into the future to see if  ack  happens, we can stand at the  ack  signal and look into
  the past to make sure  req  actually happened! It is incredibly useful for finding bugs in very messy pipelines.


  ### Family 3: The Vector Checks

  Up until now, we have mostly checked single bit wires (like  bit req ). But what if you have a 5-bit bus ( logic [4:0] state )? These 4
  methods are specifically built to check multi-bit vectors!

  #### 5.  $onehot(bus)

  • What it does: It checks that exactly one bit in the vector is high ( 1 ), and all other bits are  0 .
  • Example:  5'b00100  will PASS.  5'b01100  will FAIL (two bits are high).  5'b00000  will FAIL (zero bits are high).
  • Syntax:

    property p_onehot;
      // Make sure the state machine is always one-hot!
      @(posedge clk) $onehot(state);
    endproperty

  #### 6.  $onehot0(bus)

  • What it does: It is exactly the same as above, but it also allows all zeros. It stands for "One-Hot or Zero".
  • Example:  5'b00100  will PASS.  5'b00000  will ALSO PASS!  5'b11000  will FAIL.

  #### 7.  $isunknown(bus)

  • What it does: It checks if any bit inside the vector accidentally became  X  (Unknown) or  Z  (High-Impedance). This is a lifesaver for
  finding uninitialized memory bugs!
  • Example:  5'b01000  will return FALSE (No unknowns).  5'b01X00  will return TRUE (It found an X!).
  • Syntax:

    property p_unknown;
      // If the bus has an X or Z, throw an error!
      @(posedge clk) $isunknown(bus) |-> 0; // Force it to fail if true
    endproperty

  #### 8.  $countones(bus)

  • What it does: Instead of returning TRUE or FALSE, it returns an integer counting exactly how many  1 s are in the vector!
  • Syntax:

    property p_count;
      // Make sure there are strictly more than 2 bits high!
      @(posedge clk) ($countones(bus) > 2);
    endproperty
    ──────


  ### Missed Topic 6: The  .ended  Construct

  Up until now, we have used the implication operator ( |-> ) to connect sequences. When we write  seq_1 |-> seq_2 , the simulator says: "If
  seq_1  is true, then start checking  seq_2 ."

  But what if you have a massive, complicated sequence that takes 10 clock cycles to finish, and you want to use the exact finishing moment
  as a trigger?

  #### What is  .ended ?

  The  .ended  keyword is attached to the name of a sequence. It acts as a synchronization point. It returns TRUE on the exact clock cycle
  that the sequence successfully finishes.

  #### Syntax & Example:

    sequence seq_1;
      @(posedge clk) d;
    endsequence

    sequence seq_2;
      @(posedge clk) ##4 k; // Wait 4 clocks, then check k
    endsequence

    // Using the .ended keyword!
    property p_ended;
      @(posedge clk)
      seq_1.ended |-> ##4 seq_2.ended;
    endproperty

  ### Why do we use it? (The Synchronization Secret)

  Let's look at the difference between using  .ended  and NOT using  .ended :

  Without  .ended :  seq_1 |-> ##4 seq_2

  • If  d  is high,  seq_1  is true.
  • The simulator waits 4 clock cycles ( ##4 ).
  • Then it STARTS  seq_2 .
  • Because  seq_2  has another  ##4  inside it, the simulator waits another 4 clock cycles, and finally checks  k !
  • Total Time Taken: 9 clock cycles!

  With  .ended :  seq_1.ended |-> ##4 seq_2.ended

  • If  d  is high,  seq_1  finishes (because it's only 1 clock long).  seq_1.ended  is now TRUE.
  • Because  seq_2  takes 4 clocks to run, and we just waited 4 clocks, the simulator looks at  k  immediately!
  • The simulator waits 4 clock cycles ( ##4 ).
  • Instead of starting  seq_2  from the beginning, the simulator demands that  seq_2  must FINISH exactly right now!
  • Total Time Taken: 5 clock cycles!




